# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: scissors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] An **abrasive saw**, also known as a **cut-off saw** or **chop saw**, is a circular saw (a kind of power tool) which is typically used to cut hard materials, such as metals, tile, and concrete.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] The cutting action is performed by an abrasive disc, similar to a thin grinding wheel.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] Technically speaking this is not a saw, as it does not use regularly shaped edges (teeth) for cutting.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] These saws are available in a number of configurations, including table top, free hand, and walk behind models.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] In the table top models, which are commonly used to cut tile and metal, the cutting wheel and motor are mounted on a pivoting arm attached to a fixed base plate.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] Table top saws are often electrically powered and generally have a built-in vise or other clamping arrangement.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] The free hand designs are typically used to cut concrete, asphalt, and pipe on construction sites.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] They are designed with the handles and motor near the operator, with the blade at the far end of the saw.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] Free hand saws do not feature a vise, because the materials being cut are larger and heavier.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] Walk-behind models, sometimes called flat saws are larger saws which use a stand or cart to cut into concrete floors as well as asphalt and concrete paving materials.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] Abrasive saws typically use composite friction disk blades known as "cutoff wheels/blades" to abrasively cut through the steel.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] The blades are consumable items as they wear throughout the cut.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] The abrasive blades for these saws are typically 14 in (360 mm) in diameter and 7⁄64 in (2.8 mm) thick, though they can be thousandths of an inch thick and only 2" in diameter.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] Larger saws use 410 mm (16 in) diameter blades.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] Blades are available for steel and stainless steel.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] Abrasive saws can also use superabrasive (i.e., diamond and cubic boron nitride or CBN) blades, which last longer than conventional abrasive materials and do not generate as hazardous particulate matter.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] Superabrasive materials are more commonly used when cutting concrete, asphalt, and tile; however, they are also suitable for cutting ferrous metals.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] Rubber-bonded abrasives are a niche but important sector of the abrasive cutoff wheel manufacturing space.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] These blades can be extremely thin and use specialized machines known as "Cutoff Machines".
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] These machines use the extremely thin rubber-bonded wheels to reduce loss of material compared to a thicker-metal blade which would produce burring, lose more material, and cause inconsistent finishes.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] Rubber-bonded blades finish as they cut reducing the time it take to produce sections of materials such as Molybdenum, Inconel, Steel, Iron, Brass, and more.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] Many industries such as the aerospace industry and automotive industry use these wheels to produce fasteners and bolts with extremely precise measurements.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] Since their introduction, portable cut-off saws have made many building site jobs easier.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] With these saws, lightweight steel fabrication previously performed in workshops using stationary power bandsaws or cold saws can be done on-site.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] Abrasive saws have replaced more expensive and hazardous acetylene torches in many applications, such as cutting rebar.
[src:scissors/abrasive-saw] In addition, these saws allow construction workers to cut through concrete, asphalt, and pipe on job sites in a more precise manner than is possible with heavy equipment.
[src:scissors/abrasive] An **abrasive** is a material, often a mineral, that is used to shape or finish a workpiece through rubbing which leads to part of the workpiece being worn away by friction.
[src:scissors/abrasive] While finishing a material often means polishing it to gain a smooth, reflective surface, the process can also involve roughening as in satin, matte or beaded finishes.
[src:scissors/abrasive] In short, the ceramics which are used to cut, grind and polish other softer materials are known as abrasives.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Abrasives are extremely commonplace and are used very extensively in a wide variety of industrial, domestic, and technological applications.
[src:scissors/abrasive] This gives rise to a large variation in the physical and chemical composition of abrasives as well as the shape of the abrasive.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Some common uses for abrasives include grinding, polishing, buffing, honing, cutting, drilling, sharpening, lapping, and sanding (see abrasive machining).
[src:scissors/abrasive] Files are not abrasives; they remove material not by scratching or rubbing, but by the cutting action of sharp teeth which have been cut into the surface of the file, very much like those of a saw.
[src:scissors/abrasive] However, diamond files are a form of coated abrasive (as they are metal rods coated with diamond powder).
[src:scissors/abrasive] Abrasives generally rely upon a difference in hardness between the abrasive and the material being worked upon, the abrasive being the harder of the two substances.
[src:scissors/abrasive] However, it is not strictly necessary, as any two solid materials that repeatedly rub against each other will tend to wear each other away; examples include, softer shoe soles wearing away wooden or stone steps over decades or centuries or glaciers abrading stone valleys.
[src:scissors/abrasive] However, even softer minerals like calcium carbonate are used as abrasives, such as "polishing agents" in toothpaste.
[src:scissors/abrasive] These minerals are either crushed or are already of a sufficiently small size (anywhere from macroscopic grains as large as about 2 mm to microscopic grains about 0.001 mm in diameter) to permit their use as an abrasive.
[src:scissors/abrasive] These grains, commonly called grit, have rough edges, often terminating in points which will decrease the surface area in contact and increase the localised contact pressure.
[src:scissors/abrasive] The abrasive and the material to be worked are brought into contact while in relative motion to each other.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Force applied through the grains causes fragments of the worked material to break away, while simultaneously smoothing the abrasive grain and/or causing the grain to work loose from the rest of the abrasive.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Abrasives may be classified as either natural or synthetic.
[src:scissors/abrasive] When discussing sharpening stones, natural stones have long been considered superior but advances in material technology are seeing this distinction become less distinct.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Many synthetic abrasives are effectively identical to a natural mineral, differing only in that the synthetic mineral has been manufactured rather than mined.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Impurities in the natural mineral may make it less effective.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Some abrasive minerals (such as zirconia alumina) occur naturally but are sufficiently rare or sufficiently more difficult or costly to obtain such that a synthetic stone is used industrially.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Abrasives are shaped for various purposes.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Natural abrasives are often sold as dressed stones, usually in the form of a rectangular block.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Both natural and synthetic abrasives are commonly available in a wide variety of shapes, often coming as bonded or coated abrasives, including blocks, belts, discs, wheels, sheets, rods and loose grains.
[src:scissors/abrasive] A **bonded abrasive** is composed of an abrasive material contained within a matrix, although very fine aluminium oxide abrasive may comprise sintered material.
[src:scissors/abrasive] This matrix is called a binder and is often a clay, a resin, a glass or a rubber.
[src:scissors/abrasive] This mixture of binder and abrasive is typically shaped into blocks, sticks, or wheels.
[src:scissors/abrasive] The most common abrasive used is aluminium oxide.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Also common are silicon carbide, tungsten carbide and garnet.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Artificial sharpening stones are often a bonded abrasive and are readily available as a two sided block, each side being a different grade of grit.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Grinding wheels are cylinders that are rotated at high speed.
[src:scissors/abrasive] While once worked with a foot pedal or hand crank, the introduction of electric motors has made it necessary to construct the wheel to withstand greater radial stress to prevent the wheel flying apart as it spins.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Similar issues arise with cutting wheels, which are often structurally reinforced with impregnated fibres.
[src:scissors/abrasive] High relative speed between abrasive and workpiece often makes necessary the use of a lubricant of some kind.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Traditionally, they were called coolants as they were used to prevent frictional heat build up which could damage the workpiece (such as ruining the temper of a blade).
[src:scissors/abrasive] Some research suggests that the heat transport property of a lubricant is less important when dealing with metals as the metal will quickly conduct heat from the work surface.
[src:scissors/abrasive] More important are their effects upon lessening tensile stresses while increasing some compressive stresses and reducing "thermal and mechanical stresses during chip formation".
[src:scissors/abrasive] Various shapes are also used as heads on rotary tools used in precision work, such as scale modelling.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Bonded abrasives need to be trued and dressed after they are used.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Dressing is the cleaning of the waste material (swarf and loose abrasive) from the surface and exposing fresh grit.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Depending upon the abrasive and how it was used, dressing may involve the abrasive being simply placed under running water and brushed with a stiff brush for a soft stone or the abrasive being ground against another abrasive, such as aluminium oxide used to dress a grinding wheel.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Truing is restoring the abrasive to its original surface shape.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Wheels and stones tend to wear unevenly, leaving the cutting surface no longer flat (said to be "dished out" if it is meant to be a flat stone) or no longer the same diameter across the cutting face.
[src:scissors/abrasive] This will lead to uneven abrasion and other difficulties.
[src:scissors/abrasive] A *coated abrasive* comprises an abrasive fixed to a backing material such as paper, cloth, rubber, resin, polyester or even metal, many of which are flexible.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Sandpaper is a very common coated abrasive.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Coated abrasives are most commonly the same minerals as are used for bonded abrasives.
[src:scissors/abrasive] A bonding agent (often some sort of adhesive or resin) is applied to the backing to provide a flat surface to which the grit is then subsequently adhered.
[src:scissors/abrasive] A woven backing may also use a filler agent (again, often a resin) to provide additional resilience.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Coated abrasives may be shaped for use in rotary and orbital sanders, for wrapping around sanding blocks, as handpads, as closed loops for use on belt grinders, as striking surfaces on matchboxes, on diamond plates and diamond steels.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Diamond tools, though for cutting, are often abrasive in nature.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Sand, glass beads, metal pellets copper slag and dry ice may all be used for a process called sandblasting (or similar, such as the use of glass beads which is "bead blasting").
[src:scissors/abrasive] Dry ice will sublimate leaving behind no residual abrasive.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Cutting compound used on automotive paint is an example of an abrasive suspended in a liquid, paste or wax, as are some polishing liquids for silverware and optical media.
[src:scissors/abrasive] The liquid, paste or wax acts as a binding agent that keeps the abrasive attached to the cloth which is used as a backing to move the abrasive across the work piece.
[src:scissors/abrasive] On cars in particular, wax may serve as both a protective agent by preventing exposure of the paint of metal to air and also act as an optical filler to make scratches less noticeable.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Toothpaste contains calcium carbonate or silica as a "polishing agent" to remove plaque and other matter from teeth as the hardness of calcium carbonate is less than that of tooth enamel but more than that of the contaminating agent.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Very fine rouge powder was commonly used for grinding glass, being somewhat replaced by modern ceramics, and is still used in jewellery making for a highly reflective finish.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Cleaning products may also contain abrasives suspended in a paste or cream.
[src:scissors/abrasive] They are chosen to be reasonably safe on some linoleum, tile, metal or stone surfaces.
[src:scissors/abrasive] However, many laminate surfaces and ceramic topped stoves are easily damaged by these abrasive compounds.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Even ceramic/pottery tableware or cookware can damage these surfaces, particularly the bottom of the tableware, which is often unglazed in part or in whole and acts as simply another bonded abrasive.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Metal pots and stoves are often scoured with abrasive cleaners, typically in the form of the aforementioned cream or paste or of steel wool and non woven scouring pads which holds fine grits abrasives.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Human skin is also subjected to abrasion in the form of exfoliation.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Abrasives for this can be much softer and more exotic than for other purposes and may include things like almond and oatmeal.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Dermabrasion and microdermabrasion are now rather commonplace cosmetic procedures which use mineral abrasives.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Scratched compact discs and DVDs may sometimes be repaired through buffing with a very fine compound, the principle being that a multitude of small scratches will be more optically transparent than a single large scratch.
[src:scissors/abrasive] However, this does take some skill and will eventually cause the protective coating of the disc to be entirely eroded (especially if the original scratch is deep), at which time, the data surface will be destroyed if abrasion continues.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Silicon carbide powders are commonly used as abrasive materials in various machining processes, including grinding, water-jet cutting, and sandblasting.
[src:scissors/abrasive] These powders are effective for fine grinding or rough polishing of semiconductors, ceramics, and ferrous materials.
[src:scissors/abrasive] The shape, size and nature of the workpiece and the desired finish will influence the choice of the abrasive used.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Also, different shapes of adhesive may make it harder to abrade certain areas of the workpiece.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Health hazards can arise from any dust produced (which may be ameliorated through the use of a lubricant) which could lead to silicosis (when the abrasive or workpiece is a silicate) and the choice of any lubricant.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Besides water, oils are the most common lubricants.
[src:scissors/abrasive] These may present inhalation hazards, contact hazards and, as friction necessarily produces heat, flammable material hazards.
[src:scissors/abrasive] An abrasive which is too hard or too coarse can remove too much material or leave undesired scratch marks.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Besides being unsightly, scratching can have other, more serious effects.
[src:scissors/abrasive] A finer or softer abrasive will tend to leave much finer scratch marks which may even be invisible to the naked eye (a "grainless finish"); a softer abrasive may not even significantly abrade a certain object.
[src:scissors/abrasive] A softer or finer abrasive will take longer to cut, as it tends to cut less deeply than a coarser, harder material.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Also, the softer abrasive may become less effective more quickly as the abrasive is itself abraded.
[src:scissors/abrasive] This allows fine abrasives to be used in the polishing of metal and lenses where the series of increasingly fine scratches tends to take on a much more shiny or reflective appearance or greater transparency.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Very fine abrasives may be used to coat the strop for a cut-throat razors, however, the purpose of stropping is not to abrade material but to straighten the burr on an edge.
[src:scissors/abrasive] The final stage of sharpening Japanese swords is called polishing and may be a form of superfinishing.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Different chemical or structural modifications may be made to alter the cutting properties of the abrasive.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Other very important considerations are price and availability.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Diamond, for a long time considered the hardest substance in existence, is actually softer than fullerite and even harder aggregated diamond nanorods, both of which have been synthesised in laboratories, but no commercial process has yet been developed.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Diamond itself is expensive due to scarcity in nature and the cost of synthesising it.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Bauxite is a very common ore which, along with corundum's reasonably high hardness, contributes to corundum's status as a common, inexpensive abrasive.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Thought must be given to the desired task about using an appropriately hard abrasive.
[src:scissors/abrasive] At one end, using an excessively hard abrasive wastes money by wearing it down when a cheaper, less hard abrasive would suffice.
[src:scissors/abrasive] At the other end, if the abrasive substance is too soft, abrasion does not take place in a timely fashion, effectively wasting the abrasive as well as any accruing costs associated with loss of time.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Aside from the aforementioned uses of shaping and finishing, abrasives may also be used to prepare surfaces for application of some sort of paint of adhesive.
[src:scissors/abrasive] An excessively smooth surface may prevent paint and adhesives from adhering as strongly as an irregular surface could allow.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Inflatable tyre repair kits (which, on bicycles particularly, are actually patches for the inner tube rather than the tyre) require use of an abrasive so that the self-vulcanising cement will stick strongly.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Inadvertently, people who use knives on glass or metal cutting boards are abrading their knife blades.
[src:scissors/abrasive] The pressure at the knife edge can easily create microscopic (or even macroscopic) cuts in the board.
[src:scissors/abrasive] This cut is a ready source of abrasive material as well as a channel full of this abrasive through which the edge slides.
[src:scissors/abrasive] For this reason, and without regard for the health benefits, wooden boards are much more desirable.
[src:scissors/abrasive] A similar occurrence arises with glass-cutters.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Glass-cutters have circular blades that are designed to roll not slide.
[src:scissors/abrasive] They should never retrace an already effected cut.
[src:scissors/abrasive] Undesired abrasion may result from the presence of carbon in internal combustion engines.
[src:scissors/abrasive] While smaller particles are readily transported by the lubrication system, larger carbon particles may abrade components with close tolerances.
[src:scissors/abrasive] The carbon arises from the excessive heating of engine oil or from incomplete combustion.
[src:scissors/abrasive] This soot may contain fullerenes which are noted for their extreme hardness—and small size and limited quantity which would tend to limit their effect.
[src:scissors/adze] An **adze** (/ædz/) or **adz** is an ancient and versatile cutting tool similar to an axe but with the cutting edge perpendicular to the handle rather than parallel.
[src:scissors/adze] Adzes have been used since the Stone Age.
[src:scissors/adze] They are used for smoothing or carving wood in hand woodworking, and as a hoe for agriculture and horticulture.
[src:scissors/adze] Two basic forms of an adze are the hand adze (short hoe)—a short-handled tool swung with one hand—and the foot adze (hoe)—a long-handled tool capable of powerful swings using both hands, the cutting edge usually striking at foot or shin level.
[src:scissors/adze] A similar tool is called a mattock, which differs by having two blades, one perpendicular to the handle and one parallel.
[src:scissors/adze] The adze is depicted in ancient Egyptian art from the Old Kingdom onward.
[src:scissors/adze] Originally the adze blades were made of stone, but already in the Predynastic Period copper adzes had all but replaced those made of flint.
[src:scissors/adze] Stone blades were fastened to the handle by tying and early bronze blades continued this simple construction.
[src:scissors/adze] It was not until the later Bronze Age that the handle passes through an eye at the top of the blade.
[src:scissors/adze] Examples of Egyptian adzes can be found in museums and on the Petrie Museum website.
[src:scissors/adze] The *ahnetjer* (Manuel de Codage transliteration: *aH-nTr*) depicted as an adze-like instrument, was used in the Opening of the Mouth ceremony, intended to convey power over their senses to statues and mummies.
[src:scissors/adze] It was apparently the foreleg of a freshly sacrificed bull or cow with which the mouth was touched.
[src:scissors/adze] As Iron Age technology moved south into Africa with migrating ancient Egyptians, they carried their technology with them, including adzes.
[src:scissors/adze] To this day, iron adzes are used all over rural Africa for various purposes—from digging pit latrines, and chopping firewood, to tilling crop fields—whether they are of maize (corn), coffee, tea, pyrethrum, beans, millet, yams, or a plethora of other cash and subsistence crops.
[src:scissors/adze] Prehistoric Māori adzes from New Zealand were for wood carving, typically made from pounamu sourced from the South Island.
[src:scissors/adze] During the Māori Archaic period found on the North Island were commonly made from greywacke from Motutapu Island or basalt from Opito Bay in the Coromandel, similar to adzes constructed on other Pacific Islands.
[src:scissors/adze] Early period notched adzes found in Northland were primarily made of argillite quarried from locations around the Marlborough and Nelson regions.
[src:scissors/adze] At the same time on Henderson Island, a small coral island in eastern Polynesia lacking any rock other than limestone, native populations may have fashioned giant clamshells into adzes.
[src:scissors/adze] American Northwest coast native peoples traditionally used adzes for both functional construction (from bowls to canoes) and art (from masks to totem poles).
[src:scissors/adze] Northwest coast adzes take two forms: hafted and D-handle.
[src:scissors/adze] The hafted form is similar in form to a European adze with the haft constructed from a natural crooked branch which approximately forms a 60% angle.
[src:scissors/adze] The thin end is used as the handle and the thick end is flattened and notched such that an adze iron can be lashed to it.
[src:scissors/adze] Modern hafts are sometimes constructed from a sawed blank with a dowel added for strength at the crook.
[src:scissors/adze] The second form is the D-handle adze which is basically an adze iron with a directly attached handle.
[src:scissors/adze] The D-handle, therefore, provides no mechanical leverage.
[src:scissors/adze] Northwest coast adzes are often classified by size and iron shape vs. role.
[src:scissors/adze] As with European adzes, iron shapes include straight, gutter and lipped.
[src:scissors/adze] Where larger Northwest adzes are similar in size to their European counterparts, the smaller sizes are typically much lighter such that they can be used for the detailed smoothing, shaping and surface texturing required for figure carving.
[src:scissors/adze] Final surfacing is sometimes performed with a crooked knife.
[src:scissors/adze] Ground stone adzes used to be produced by a variety of people in Western New Guinea (Indonesia), Papua New Guinea and some of the smaller Islands of Melanesia and Micronesia.
[src:scissors/adze] The hardstone would have been ground on a riverine rock with the help of water until the desired shape was obtained.
[src:scissors/adze] It was then fixed to a natural grown angled wood with resin and plant fibers.
[src:scissors/adze] Imported steel axes or machetes have now entirely replaced these tools for decades in even the remotest parts of New Guinea.
[src:scissors/adze] Indeed, even before the first foreign missionaries or colonial officials arrived in the New Guinea Highlands, inhabitants had already obtained steel tools through trade with their neighbors.
[src:scissors/adze] Stone tools are sometimes manufactured to be sold as curios to tourists.
[src:scissors/adze] Modern adzes are made from steel with wooden handles, and enjoy limited use: occasionally in semi-industrial areas, but particularly by "revivalists" such as those at the Colonial Williamsburg cultural center in Virginia, United States.
[src:scissors/adze] However, the traditional adze has largely been replaced by the sawmill and the powered plane, at least in industrialised cultures.
[src:scissors/adze] It remains in use for some specialist crafts, for example by coopers.
[src:scissors/adze] Adzes are also in current use by artists such as Northwest Coast American and Canadian Indigenous sculptors doing totem pole carving, as well as masks and bowls.
[src:scissors/adze] "Adzes are used for removing heavy waste, leveling, shaping, or trimming the surfaces of timber" and boards.
[src:scissors/adze] Generally, the user stands astride a board or log and swings the adze downwards between his feet, chipping off pieces of wood, moving backwards as they go and leaving a relatively smooth surface behind.
[src:scissors/adze] Foot adzes are most commonly known as shipbuilder's or carpenter's adzes.
[src:scissors/adze] On the modern, steel adze the cutting edge may be flat for smoothing work to very rounded for hollowing work such as bowls, gutters and canoes.
[src:scissors/adze] The shoulders or sides of an adze may be curved called a *lipped adze*, used for notching.
[src:scissors/adze] The end away from the cutting edge is called the pole and be of different shapes, generally flat or a *pin pole*.
[src:scissors/adze] There are a number of specialist, short-handled adzes used by coopers, wainwrights, and chair makers, and in bowl and trough making.
[src:scissors/adze] Many of these have shorter handles for control and more curve in the head to allow better clearance for shorter cuts.
[src:scissors/adze] During the communist period of Bulgaria, a new multi-use woodworking adze, called Теслà (*Teslà*), emerged.
[src:scissors/adze] It has a sharpened edge perpendicular to the handle, resembling an adze, but it is also used like a carpenter's hammer.
[src:scissors/adze] On the back of the head is a textured poll for driving nails, and on the front is a V-shaped hole used for prying, to extract the bent nails.
[src:scissors/adze] There is a popular Bulgarian folk song called "На теслата дръжката" (eng: The tesla's handle) about a craftsman and the masculinity of his tool.
[src:scissors/afghan-blanket] An **afghan** is a blanket or shawl, usually knitted or crocheted.
[src:scissors/afghan-blanket] It is sometimes also called a **throw**.
[src:scissors/afghan-blanket] Afghans are often used as bedspreads, or as a decoration on the back of couches or chairs.
[src:scissors/afghan-blanket] The word *afghan* refers to the people of Afghanistan.
[src:scissors/afghan-blanket] The use of *afghan* in the English language for a textile object goes back to at least 1831, when Thomas Carlyle mentioned "Afghan shawls" in his *Sartor Resartus*.
[src:scissors/afghan-blanket] The Afghan blankets and shawls may have roots in the rich textile tradition of Afghanistan which consisted of geometric designs made with many crocheted or knitted squares of yarn sewn together into a fabric.
[src:scissors/aida-cloth] Aida cloth is manufactured with various size spaces or holes between the warp and weft to accommodate different thicknesses of yarn.
[src:scissors/aida-cloth] For example, a 10-count Aida cloth would have 10 squares per linear inch.
[src:scissors/aida-cloth] Typical sizes are 7, 10, 11, 12, 14, 16, 18 and 20 count, ranked from the coarsest to the finest count.
[src:scissors/aida-cloth] Traditional colours are white and ecru, though black, grey, shades of tan and brown, and other brighter colors are also available.
[src:scissors/aida-cloth] Aida cloth is sold in precut sheets or in bolts of 40" - 60" width at most craft stores.
[src:scissors/aida-cloth] Aida cloth has a tendency to fray and often needs hemming before use.
[src:scissors/aida-cloth] It should never be laundered prior to craft work and tends to contract when the finished item is washed in soap and water.
[src:scissors/aida-cloth] Hand washing improves the appearance of finished cross-stitching because Aida cloth naturally contracts in specific areas where it is embroidered.
[src:scissors/aida-cloth] The consensus from various discussions on Usenet group *rec.crafts.textiles.needlework* is that there are two ways to pronounce the word "Aida": either /ɑːˈiːdə/, as in the opera by Verdi, or /ˈeɪdə/.
[src:scissors/aida-cloth] Since the name change from *Java* to *Aida* occurred not long after Verdi's opera was first performed, there has been some speculation that the cloth was renamed after the opera to take advantage of the opera's publicity.
[src:scissors/aida-cloth] It is another material suitable for embroidery.
[src:scissors/aida-cloth] The fabric structure (open plain weave) makes it convenient to count threads in cross-stitch work.
[src:scissors/aida-cloth] The material is used for various linens.
[src:scissors/alice-starmore] Growing up in a traditional Scottish fishing community with Gaelic as her native language, Starmore learned knitting and created her own designs by the age of five.
[src:scissors/alice-starmore] In 1975 she produced a knitwear collection which was sold in London boutiques.
[src:scissors/alice-starmore] In 1978, Starmore was awarded a Winston Churchill Fellowship, under which she travelled to Norway, Sweden and Finland to study their textile traditions.
[src:scissors/alice-starmore] She is an authority on Celtic and Fair Isle design and technique through her books, as well as articles for *Threads* and *Vogue Knitting* magazines.
[src:scissors/alice-starmore] She markets her own lines of threads and yarn.
[src:scissors/alice-starmore] In 1991 Starmore founded Windfall Press, which began with knitting titles and moved to Scottish Gaelic.
[src:scissors/alice-starmore] Starmore put on an art exhibition called "Mamba" at An Lanntair, Stornoway, Isle of Lewis during Summer 2008.
[src:scissors/alice-starmore] She has appeared at a number of textile and knitting events, including the Dutch *Stitch 'n' Bitch* Day (Rotterdam, 2006) and I Knit London's *Weekender* (September 2009).
[src:scissors/alice-starmore] Starmore photographs the natural world, particularly birds and insects, and she contributes to publications of the British Dragonfly Society.
[src:scissors/alice-starmore] She is regarded as an authority on Scottish moorland habitats, and is employed by the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds (RSPB) as their Education Officer for the Isles of Lewis and Harris.
[src:scissors/alice-starmore] Her daughter Jade is a professional needleworker and artist, and has published her own books.
[src:scissors/alice-starmore] Starmore is best known for her book on Fair Isle knitting, a traditional knitting technique used to create complex patterns with multiple, typically up to five, colours.
[src:scissors/alice-starmore] He writes "If you've ever wanted to create fair isle patterns that are uniquely your own, this is the must-have book.
[src:scissors/alice-starmore] If you've ever wondered about knitting history, this is the book.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Chemically, aluminium is a post-transition metal in the boron group; as is common for the group, aluminium forms compounds primarily in the +3 oxidation state.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The aluminium cation Al3+ is small and highly charged; as such, it has more polarizing power, and bonds formed by aluminium have a more covalent character.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The strong affinity of aluminium for oxygen leads to the common occurrence of its oxides in nature.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is found on Earth primarily in rocks in the crust, where it is the third-most abundant element after oxygen and silicon, rather than in the mantle, and virtually never as the free metal.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It is obtained industrially by mining bauxite, a sedimentary rock rich in aluminium minerals.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The discovery of aluminium was announced in 1825 by Danish physicist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was initiated by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville in 1856.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium became much more available to the public with the Hall–Héroult process developed independently by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall in 1886, and the mass production of aluminium led to its extensive use in industry and everyday life.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In 1954, aluminium became the most produced non-ferrous metal, surpassing copper.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In the 21st century, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging in the United States, Western Europe, and Japan.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The standard atomic weight of aluminium is low in comparison with many other metals, giving it the low density responsible for many of its uses.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Despite its prevalence in the environment, no living thing is known to metabolize aluminium salts, but aluminium is well tolerated by plants and animals.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Because of the abundance of these salts, the potential for a biological role for them is of interest, and studies are ongoing.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium metal has an appearance ranging from silvery white to dull gray depending on its surface roughness.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium mirrors provides high reflectivity for light in the ultraviolet, visible (on par with silver), and far infrared regions.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is also good at reflecting solar radiation, although prolonged exposure to sunlight in air can deteriorate the reflectivity of the metal; this may be prevented if aluminium is anodized, which adds a protective layer of oxide on the surface.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The density of aluminium is 2.70 g/cm3, about one-third that of steel, much lower than other commonly encountered metals, making aluminium parts easily identifiable through their lightness.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's low density compared to most other metals arises from the fact that its unit cell size is relatively large in proportion to the number of nucleons.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The only lighter metals are the metals of groups 1 and 2, which, apart from beryllium and magnesium, are too reactive for structural use (and beryllium is very toxic).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is not as strong or stiff as steel, but the low density makes up for this in the aerospace industry and for many other applications where light weight and relatively high strength are crucial.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Pure aluminium is quite soft and lacking in strength.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In most applications, various aluminium alloys are used instead because of their higher strength and hardness.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The yield strength of pure aluminium is 7–11 MPa, while aluminium alloys have yield strengths ranging from 200 MPa to 600 MPa.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is ductile, with a percent elongation of 50–70%, and malleable allowing it to be easily drawn and extruded; it is also easily machined and cast.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is an excellent thermal and electrical conductor, and the amount of aluminium required to match the same amperage in copper weighs only half as much.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is capable of superconductivity, with a superconducting critical temperature of 1.2 kelvin and a critical magnetic field of about 100 gauss (10 milliteslas).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It is paramagnetic and thus essentially unaffected by static magnetic fields.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] However, the high electrical conductivity means that it is strongly affected by alternating magnetic fields through the induction of eddy currents.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] An aluminium atom has 13 electrons with an electron configuration of [Ne] 3s2 3p1, with three electrons beyond a stable noble gas configuration.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Accordingly, the combined first three ionization energies of aluminium are far lower than the fourth ionization energy alone.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Such an electron configuration is shared with the other well-characterized members of its group, boron, gallium, indium, and thallium; it is also expected for nihonium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium can surrender its three outermost electrons in many chemical reactions (see below).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The electronegativity of aluminium is 1.61 on the Pauling scale.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] A free aluminium atom has an atomic radius of 143 pm.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] With the three outermost electrons removed, the radius shrinks to 39 pm for a 4-coordinated atom or 53.5 pm for a 6-coordinated atom.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] At standard temperature and pressure, aluminium atoms (when not affected by atoms of other elements) form a face-centered cubic crystal system bound by metallic bonding provided by atoms' outermost electrons; hence, aluminium (at these conditions) is a metal.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] This crystal system is shared by many other metals, such as lead and copper; the size of a unit cell of aluminium is comparable to that of those other metals.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] This system, however, is not shared by the other members of its group: boron has ionization energies too high to allow metallization, thallium has a hexagonal close-packed structure, and gallium and indium have unusual structures that are not close-packed like those of aluminium and thallium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The few electrons that are available for metallic bonding in aluminium are a probable cause for it being soft with a low melting point and low electrical resistivity.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium has one stable isotope, 27Al, which comprises virtually all of the naturally-occurring element.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] This is common for elements with an odd atomic number.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It is therefore a mononuclidic element for standard atomic weight, which is determined completely by that isotope.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is useful in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR), as its single stable isotope (though quadrupolar) has a high NMR sensitivity.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] All other isotopes of aluminium are radioactive.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The most stable of these is 26Al, with a half-life of 717,000 years.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] While it was present along with stable 27Al in the interstellar medium from which the Solar System formed (believed to have been produced by stellar nucleosynthesis also), no detectable amount could have survived the time since the formation of the planet.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] However, minute traces of 26Al are still produced from decay of argon in the atmosphere induced by ionizing radiation of cosmic rays.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The ratio of 26Al to 10Be has been used for the radiodating of geological processes over 105 to 106 year time scales, in particular transport, deposition, sediment storage, burial times, and erosion.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Most meteorite scientists believe that the energy released by the decay of 26Al was responsible for the melting and differentiation of some asteroids after their formation 4.55 billion years ago.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The other known isotopes of aluminium, with mass numbers ranging from 20 to 43, all have half-lives less than 7 minutes, as do the four detected metastable states.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium combines characteristics of pre- and post-transition metals.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Since it has few available electrons for metallic bonding, like the heavier group 13 elements, it has the characteristic physical properties of a post-transition metal, with longer-than-expected interatomic distances.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Furthermore, as Al3+ is a small and highly charged cation, it is strongly polarizing, and bonding in aluminium compounds tends towards covalency; this behavior is similar to that of beryllium (Be2+), displaying an example of a diagonal relationship.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The underlying core of electrons under aluminium's valence shell is that of the preceding noble gas, whereas those of the heavier group 13 elements gallium, indium, thallium, and nihonium also include a filled d-subshell and in some cases a filled f-subshell.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Hence, the inner electrons of aluminium shield the valence electrons almost completely, unlike those of the heavier group 13 elements.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] As such, aluminium is the most electropositive metal in its group, and its hydroxide is in fact more basic than that of gallium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also bears minor similarities to boron (a metalloid), which is in the same group: AlX3 compounds are valence isoelectronic to BX3 compounds (they have the same valence electronic structure), and both behave as Lewis acids and readily form adducts.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Additionally, one of the main motifs of boron chemistry is regular icosahedral structures, and aluminium forms an important part of many icosahedral quasicrystal alloys, including the Al–Zn–Mg class.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium has a high chemical affinity to oxygen, which renders it suitable for use as a reducing agent in the thermite reaction.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] A fine powder of aluminium reacts explosively on contact with liquid oxygen; under normal conditions, however, aluminium forms a thin oxide layer (~5 nm at room temperature) that protects the metal from further corrosion by oxygen, water, or dilute acid, a process termed passivation.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is not attacked by oxidizing acids because of its passivation.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] This allows aluminium to be used to store reagents such as nitric acid, concentrated sulfuric acid, and some organic acids.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In hot, concentrated hydrochloric acid, aluminium reacts with water through evolution of hydrogen, and it reacts in aqueous sodium or potassium hydroxide at room temperature to form aluminates; protective passivation under these conditions is negligible.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is also corroded by dissolved chlorides, such as common sodium chloride.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The oxide layer on aluminium is also destroyed by contact with mercury due to amalgamation or by contact with salts of some electropositive metals.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] As such, the strongest aluminium alloys are less corrosion-resistant due to galvanic reactions with alloyed copper, and aluminium's corrosion resistance is greatly reduced by aqueous salts, particularly in the presence of dissimilar metals.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium reacts with most nonmetals upon heating, forming compounds such as aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), and the aluminium halides (AlX3).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It also forms a wide range of intermetallic compounds involving metals from every group on the periodic table.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The vast majority of aluminium compounds, including all aluminium-containing minerals and all commercially significant aluminium compounds, feature aluminium in the oxidation state 3+.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The coordination number of such compounds varies, but generally Al3+ is either six- or four-coordinate.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Almost all compounds of aluminium(III) are colorless.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In aqueous solution, Al3+ exists as the hexa-aqua cation [Al(H2O)6]3+, which has an approximate Ka of 10−5.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Such solutions are acidic because this cation can act as a proton donor and progressively hydrolyze until a precipitate of aluminium hydroxide, Al(OH)3, forms.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] This is useful for clarification of water, since the precipitate nucleates on suspended particles in the water, hence removing them.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Increasing the pH even further leads to the hydroxide dissolving again as aluminate, [Al(H2O)2(OH)4]−, is formed.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium hydroxide forms both salts and aluminates and dissolves in acid and alkali, as well as on fusion with acidic and basic oxides.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] This behavior of Al(OH)3 is termed amphoterism and is characteristic of weakly basic cations that form insoluble hydroxides and whose hydrated species can also donate their protons.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] One effect of this is that aluminium salts with weak acids are hydrolyzed in water to the aquated hydroxide and the corresponding nonmetal hydride: for example, aluminium sulfide yields hydrogen sulfide.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] However, some salts like aluminium carbonate exist in aqueous solution but are unstable as such.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Only incomplete hydrolysis takes place for salts with strong acids, such as the halides, nitrate, and sulfate.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] For similar reasons, anhydrous aluminium salts cannot be made by heating their "hydrates": hydrated aluminium chloride is in fact not AlCl3·6H2O but [Al(H2O)6]Cl3, and the Al–O bonds are so strong that heating is not sufficient to break them and form Al–Cl bonds.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Unlike the structures of the three heavier trihalides, aluminium fluoride (AlF3) features six-coordinate aluminium, which explains its involatility and insolubility as well as high heat of formation.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Each aluminium atom is surrounded by six fluorine atoms in a distorted octahedral arrangement, with each fluorine atom being shared between the corners of two octahedra.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Such {AlF6} units also exist in complex fluorides such as cryolite, Na3AlF6.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] AlF3 melts at 1,290 °C (2,354 °F) and is made by reaction of aluminium oxide with hydrogen fluoride gas at 700 °C (1,300 °F).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] With heavier halides, the coordination numbers are lower.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The other trihalides are dimeric or polymeric with tetrahedral four-coordinate aluminium centers.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride (AlCl3) has a layered polymeric structure below its melting point of 192.4 °C (378 °F) but transforms on melting to Al2Cl6 dimers.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] At higher temperatures those increasingly dissociate into trigonal planar AlCl3 monomers similar to the structure of BCl3.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium tribromide and aluminium triiodide form Al2X6 dimers in all three phases and hence do not show such significant changes of properties upon phase change.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] These materials are prepared by treating aluminium with the halogen.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The aluminium trihalides form many addition compounds or complexes.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Their Lewis acidic nature makes them useful as catalysts for the Friedel–Crafts reactions.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride has major industrial uses involving this reaction, such as in the manufacture of anthraquinones and styrene.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium trichloride is also often used as the precursor for many other aluminium compounds and as a reagent for converting nonmetal fluorides into the corresponding chlorides (a transhalogenation reaction).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium forms one stable oxide with the chemical formula Al2O3, commonly called alumina.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It can be found in nature in the mineral corundum, the α-alumina phase.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Its crystalline form, corundum, is very hard (Mohs hardness 9), has a high melting point of 2,045 °C (3,713 °F), has very low volatility, is chemically inert, and is a good electrical insulator.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It is often used in abrasives (such as sandpaper) as a refractory material and in ceramics.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It is also the starting material for the electrolytic production of aluminium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Sapphire and ruby are impure corundum contaminated with trace amounts of other metals.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The two main oxide-hydroxides, AlO(OH), are boehmite and diaspore.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] There are three main trihydroxides: bayerite, gibbsite, and nordstrandite, which differ in their crystalline structure (polymorphs).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Many other intermediate and related structures are also known.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Most of these Al-O-OH systems are produced from ores by a variety of wet processes using acid and bases.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Heating the hydroxides leads to the formation of corundum.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] These materials are of central importance to the production of aluminium and are themselves extremely useful.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Some mixed oxide phases are also very useful, such as spinel (MgAl2O4), Na-β-alumina (NaAl11O17), and tricalcium aluminate (Ca3Al2O6), an important mineral phase in Portland cement.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The only stable chalcogenides under normal conditions are aluminium sulfide (Al2S3), selenide (Al2Se3), and telluride (Al2Te3).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] All three are prepared by direct reaction of their elements at about 1,000 °C (1,800 °F) and quickly hydrolyze completely in water to yield aluminium hydroxide and the respective hydrogen chalcogenide.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] As aluminium is a small atom relative to these chalcogens, these have four-coordinate tetrahedral aluminium with various polymorphs having structures related to wurtzite, with two-thirds of the possible metal sites occupied either in an orderly (α) or random (β) fashion.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The sulfide also has a γ form related to γ-alumina and an unusual high-temperature hexagonal form where half the aluminium atoms have tetrahedral four-coordination and the other half have trigonal bipyramidal five-coordination.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Four pnictides – aluminium nitride (AlN), aluminium phosphide (AlP), aluminium arsenide (AlAs), and aluminium antimonide (AlSb) – are known.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] They are all III-V semiconductors isoelectronic to silicon and germanium, all of which but AlN have the zinc blende structure.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] All four can be made by high-temperature (and possibly high-pressure) direct reaction of their component elements.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium alloys well with most other metals (with the exception of most alkali metals and group 13 metals) and over 150 intermetallics with other metals are known.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Preparation involves heating fixed metals together in certain proportions, followed by gradual cooling and annealing.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Bonding in them is predominantly metallic and the crystal structure primarily depends on efficiency of packing.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] There are few compounds with lower oxidation states.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Some are aluminium(I) compounds: AlF, AlCl, AlBr, and AlI all exist in the gaseous phase when the respective trihalide is heated with aluminium, and at cryogenic temperatures.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] A stable derivative of aluminium monoiodide is the cyclic adduct formed with triethylamine, Al4I4(NEt3)4.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Al2O and Al2S also exist but are very unstable.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Very simple aluminium(II) compounds are invoked or observed in the reactions of Al metal with oxidants.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] For example, aluminium monoxide, AlO, has been detected in the gas phase after explosion and in stellar absorption spectra.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] More thoroughly investigated are compounds of the formula R4Al2 which contain an Al–Al bond and where R is a large organic ligand.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] A variety of compounds of empirical formula AlR3 and AlR1.5Cl1.5 exist.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The aluminium trialkyls and triaryls are either reactive, volatile, and colorless liquids or low-melting solids.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] They catch fire spontaneously in air and react with water, thus necessitating precautions when handling them.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] They often form dimers, unlike their boron analogues, but this tendency diminishes for branched-chain alkyls (e.g.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] For example, triisobutylaluminium exists as an equilibrium mixture of the monomer and dimer.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] These dimers, such as trimethylaluminium (Al2Me6), usually feature tetrahedral Al centers formed by dimerization with some alkyl group bridging between both aluminium atoms.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] They are hard acids and react readily with ligands, forming adducts.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In industry, they are mostly used in alkene insertion reactions, as discovered by Karl Ziegler, most importantly in "growth reactions" that form long-chain unbranched primary alkenes and alcohols, and in the low-pressure polymerization of ethene and propene.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] There are also some heterocyclic and cluster organoaluminium compounds involving Al–N bonds.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The industrially most important aluminium hydride is lithium aluminium hydride (LiAlH4), which is used as a reducing agent in organic chemistry.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It can be produced from lithium hydride and aluminium trichloride.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The simplest hydride, aluminium hydride or alane, is not as important.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It is a polymer with the formula (AlH3)*n*, which is in contrast to the corresponding boron hydride that is a dimer with the formula (BH3)2.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's per-particle abundance in the Solar System is 3.15 ppm (parts per million).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It is the twelfth most abundant of all elements and third most abundant among the elements that have odd atomic numbers, after hydrogen and nitrogen.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The only stable isotope of aluminium, 27Al, is the eighteenth most abundant nucleus in the universe.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It is created almost entirely after fusion of carbon in massive stars that will later become Type II supernovas: this fusion creates 26Mg, which upon capturing free protons and neutrons, becomes aluminium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Some smaller quantities of 27Al are created in hydrogen burning shells of evolved stars, where 26Mg can capture free protons.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Essentially all aluminium now in existence is 27Al.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] 26Al was present in the early Solar System with abundance of 0.005% relative to 27Al but its half-life of 728,000 years is too short for any original nuclei to survive; 26Al is therefore extinct.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Unlike for 27Al, hydrogen burning is the primary source of 26Al, with the nuclide emerging after a nucleus of 25Mg catches a free proton.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] However, the trace quantities of 26Al that do exist are the most common gamma ray emitter in the interstellar gas; if the original 26Al were still present, gamma ray maps of the Milky Way would be brighter.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Overall, the Earth is about 1.59% aluminium by mass (seventh in abundance by mass).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium occurs in greater proportion in the Earth's crust than in the universe at large.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] This is because aluminium easily forms the oxide and becomes bound into rocks and stays in the Earth's crust, while less reactive metals sink to the core.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In the Earth's crust, aluminium is the most abundant metallic element (8.23% by mass) and the third most abundant of all elements (after oxygen and silicon).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] A large number of silicates in the Earth's crust contain aluminium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In contrast, the Earth's mantle is only 2.38% aluminium by mass.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also occurs in seawater at a concentration of 0.41 μg/kg.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Because of its strong affinity for oxygen, aluminium is almost never found in the elemental state; instead it is found in oxides or silicates.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Feldspars, the most common group of minerals in the Earth's crust, are aluminosilicates.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium also occurs in the minerals beryl, cryolite, garnet, spinel, and turquoise.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Impurities in alumina yield gemstones: for example, chromium yields ruby and iron yields sapphire.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Native aluminium metal is extremely rare and can only be found as a minor phase in low oxygen fugacity environments, such as the interiors of certain volcanoes.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Native aluminium has been reported in cold seeps in the northeastern continental slope of the South China Sea.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It is possible that these deposits resulted from bacterial reduction of tetrahydroxoaluminate Al(OH)4−.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Although aluminium is a common and widespread element, not all aluminium minerals are economically viable sources of the metal.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Almost all metallic aluminium is produced from the ore bauxite (AlO*x*(OH)3–2*x*).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Bauxite occurs as a weathering product of low iron and silica bedrock in tropical climatic conditions.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In 2017, most bauxite was mined in Australia, China, Guinea, and India.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The history of aluminium has been shaped by usage of alum.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The first written record of alum, made by Greek historian Herodotus, dates back to the 5th century BCE.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The ancients are known to have used alum as a dyeing mordant and for city defense as a fire-resistant coating for wood.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] After the Crusades, alum, an indispensable good in the European fabric industry, was a subject of international commerce; it was imported to Europe from the eastern Mediterranean until the mid-15th century.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The nature of alum remained unknown until Swiss physician Paracelsus suggested alum was a salt of an earth of alum around 1530.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] German doctor and chemist Andreas Libavius experimentally confirmed this in 1595.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] German chemist Friedrich Hoffmann announced his belief that the base of alum was a distinct earth in 1722.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] German chemist Andreas Sigismund Marggraf synthesized alumina in 1754 by boiling clay in sulfuric acid and subsequently adding potash.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Attempts to produce aluminium date back to 1760.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The first successful attempt, however, was completed in 1824 by Danish physicist and chemist Hans Christian Ørsted.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] He reacted anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium amalgam, yielding a lump of metal looking similar to tin.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] He presented his results and demonstrated a sample of the new metal in 1825.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In 1827, German chemist Friedrich Wöhler repeated Ørsted's experiments but did not identify any aluminium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] (The reason for this inconsistency was only discovered in 1921.) He conducted a similar experiment in the same year by mixing anhydrous aluminium chloride with potassium (the Wöhler process) and produced a powder of aluminium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In 1845, he was able to produce small pieces of the metal and described some physical properties of this metal.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] For many years thereafter, Wöhler was credited as the discoverer of aluminium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] As Wöhler's method could not yield great quantities of aluminium, the metal remained rare; its cost exceeded that of gold.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The first industrial production of aluminium was established in 1856 by French chemist Henri Étienne Sainte-Claire Deville and companions.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Sainte-Claire Deville had discovered that aluminium trichloride could be reduced by sodium, which was more convenient and less expensive than potassium, which Wöhler had used.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Even then, aluminium was still not of great purity and produced aluminium differed in properties by sample.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Because of its electricity-conducting capacity, aluminium was used as the cap of the Washington Monument, completed in 1885, the tallest building in the world at the time.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The non-corroding metal cap was intended to serve as a lightning rod peak.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The first industrial large-scale production method was independently developed in 1886 by French engineer Paul Héroult and American engineer Charles Martin Hall; it is now known as the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The Hall–Héroult process converts alumina into metal.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Austrian chemist Carl Joseph Bayer discovered a way of purifying bauxite to yield alumina, now known as the Bayer process, in 1889.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Modern production of aluminium is based on the Bayer and Hall–Héroult processes.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] As large-scale production caused aluminium prices to drop, the metal became widely used in jewelry, eyeglass frames, optical instruments, tableware, and foil, and other everyday items in the 1890s and early 20th century.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium's ability to form hard yet light alloys with other metals provided the metal with many uses at the time.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] During World War I, major governments demanded large shipments of aluminium for light strong airframes; during World War II, demand by major governments for aviation was even higher.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] From the early 20th century to 1980, the aluminium industry was characterized by cartelization, as aluminium firms colluded to keep prices high and stable.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The first aluminium cartel, the Aluminium Association, was founded in 1901 by the Pittsburgh Reduction Company (renamed Alcoa in 1907) and Aluminium Industrie AG.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The British Aluminium Company, Produits Chimiques d'Alais et de la Camargue, and Société Électro-Métallurgique de Froges also joined the cartel.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] By the mid-20th century, aluminium had become a part of everyday life and an essential component of housewares.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In 1954, production of aluminium surpassed that of copper, historically second in production only to iron, making it the most produced non-ferrous metal.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] During the mid-20th century, aluminium emerged as a civil engineering material, with building applications in both basic construction and interior finish work, and increasingly being used in military engineering, for both airplanes and armored vehicle engines.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Earth's first artificial satellite, launched in 1957, consisted of two separate aluminium semi-spheres joined and all subsequent space vehicles have used aluminium to some extent.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The aluminium can was invented in 1956 and employed as a storage for drinks in 1958.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Throughout the 20th century, the production of aluminium rose rapidly: while the world production of aluminium in 1900 was 6,800 metric tons, the annual production first exceeded 100,000 metric tons in 1916; 1,000,000 tons in 1941; 10,000,000 tons in 1971.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In the 1970s, the increased demand for aluminium made it an exchange commodity; it entered the London Metal Exchange, the oldest industrial metal exchange in the world, in 1978.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The output continued to grow: the annual production of aluminium exceeded 50,000,000 metric tons in 2013.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The real price for aluminium declined from $14,000 per metric ton in 1900 to $2,340 in 1948 (in 1998 United States dollars).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Extraction and processing costs were lowered over technological progress and the scale of the economies.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] However, the need to exploit lower-grade poorer quality deposits and the use of fast increasing input costs (above all, energy) increased the net cost of aluminium; the real price began to grow in the 1970s with the rise of energy cost.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Production moved from the industrialized countries to countries where production was cheaper.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Production costs in the late 20th century changed because of advances in technology, lower energy prices, exchange rates of the United States dollar, and alumina prices.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The BRIC countries' combined share in primary production and primary consumption grew substantially in the first decade of the 21st century.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] China is accumulating an especially large share of the world's production thanks to an abundance of resources, cheap energy, and governmental stimuli; it also increased its consumption share from 2% in 1972 to 40% in 2010.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In the United States, Western Europe, and Japan, most aluminium was consumed in transportation, engineering, construction, and packaging.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In 2021, prices for industrial metals such as aluminium have soared to near-record levels as energy shortages in China drive up costs for electricity.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The names *aluminium* and *aluminum* are derived from the word *alumine*, an obsolete term for *alumina*, the primary naturally occurring oxide of aluminium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] *Alumine* was borrowed from French, which in turn derived it from *alumen*, the classical Latin name for alum, the mineral from which it was collected.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The Latin word *alumen* stems from the Proto-Indo-European root **alu-* meaning "bitter" or "beer".
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The English name *alum* does not come directly from Latin, whereas *alumine*/*alumina* comes from the Latin word *alumen* (on declension, *alumen* changes to *alumin-*).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] British chemist Humphry Davy, who performed a number of experiments aimed to isolate the metal, is credited as the person who named the element.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The first name proposed for the metal to be isolated from alum was *alumium*, which Davy suggested in an 1808 article on his electrochemical research, published in Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It appeared that the name was created from the English word *alum* and the Latin suffix *-ium*; but it was customary then to give elements names originating in Latin, so this name was not adopted universally.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The name *alumium* was criticized by contemporary chemists from France, Germany, and Sweden, who insisted the metal should be named for the oxide, alumina, from which it would be isolated.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] One example was *Essai sur la Nomenclature chimique* (July 1811), written in French by a Swedish chemist, Jöns Jacob Berzelius, in which the name *aluminium* is given to the element that would be synthesized from alum.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] (Another article in the same journal issue also refers to the metal whose oxide is the basis of sapphire, i.e., the same metal, as to *aluminium*.) A January 1811 summary of one of Davy's lectures at the Royal Society mentioned the name *aluminium* as a possibility.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In 1812, Davy published his chemistry text *Elements of Chemical Philosophy* in which he used the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In 1812, British scientist Thomas Young wrote an anonymous review of Davy's book, in which he proposed the name *aluminium* instead of *aluminum*, which he thought had a "less classical sound".
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] This name persisted: although the *-um* spelling was occasionally used in Britain, the American scientific language used *-ium* from the start.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The French have used the spelling *aluminium* from the start.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Most scientists throughout the world used *-ium* in the 19th century; and it was entrenched in several other European languages, such as French, German, and Dutch.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In 1828, an American lexicographer, Noah Webster, entered only the *aluminum* spelling in his *American Dictionary of the English Language*.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In the 1830s, the *-um* spelling gained usage in the United States; by the 1860s, it had become the more common spelling there outside science.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In 1892, Hall used the *-um* spelling in his advertising handbill for his new electrolytic method of producing the metal, despite his constant use of the *-ium* spelling in all the patents he filed between 1886 and 1903.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It is unknown whether this spelling was introduced by mistake or intentionally, but Hall preferred *aluminum* since its introduction because it resembled *platinum*, the name of a prestigious metal.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] By 1890, both spellings had been common in the United States, the *-ium* spelling being slightly more common; by 1895, the situation had reversed; by 1900, *aluminum* had become twice as common as *aluminium*; in the next decade, the *-um* spelling dominated American usage.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In 1925, the American Chemical Society adopted the spelling *aluminum*.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) adopted *aluminium* as the standard international name for the element in 1990.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In 1993, they recognized *aluminum* as an acceptable variant; the most recent 2005 edition of the IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry also acknowledges this spelling.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] IUPAC official publications use the *-ium* spelling as primary, and they list both where it is appropriate.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Their usage is currently regional: *aluminum* dominates in the United States and Canada; *aluminium* is prevalent in the rest of the English-speaking world.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] German physicist Ludwig Wilhelm Gilbert had proposed *Thonerde-metall*, after the German *Thonerde* for alumina, in his *Annalen der Physik* but that name never caught on at all even in Germany.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Richards in 1891 found just one occurrence of *argillium* in Swedish, from the French *argille* for clay.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The production of aluminium starts with the extraction of bauxite rock from the ground.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The bauxite is processed and transformed using the Bayer process into alumina, which is then processed using the Hall–Héroult process, resulting in the final aluminium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium production is highly energy-consuming, and so the producers tend to locate smelters in places where electric power is both plentiful and inexpensive.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Production of one kilogram of aluminium requires 7 kilograms of oil energy equivalent, as compared to 1.5 kilograms for steel and 2 kilograms for plastic.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] As of 2024, the world's largest producers of aluminium were China, India, Russia, Canada, and the United Arab Emirates, while China is by far the top producer of aluminium with a world share of over 55%.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] According to the International Resource Panel's Metal Stocks in Society report, the global per capita stock of aluminium in use in society (i.e. in cars, buildings, electronics, etc.) is 80 kg (180 lb).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Much of this is in more-developed countries (350–500 kg (770–1,100 lb) per capita) rather than less-developed countries (35 kg (77 lb) per capita).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Bauxite is converted to alumina by the Bayer process.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Bauxite is blended for uniform composition and then is ground fine.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] After this reaction, the slurry is at a temperature above its atmospheric boiling point.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It is cooled by removing steam as pressure is reduced.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The bauxite residue is separated from the solution and discarded.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The solution, free of solids, is seeded with small crystals of aluminium hydroxide; this causes decomposition of the [Al(OH)4]− ions to aluminium hydroxide.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] After about half of aluminium has precipitated, the mixture is sent to classifiers.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Small crystals of aluminium hydroxide are collected to serve as seeding agents; coarse particles are converted to alumina by heating; the excess solution is removed by evaporation, (if needed) purified, and recycled.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The conversion of alumina to aluminium is achieved by the Hall–Héroult process.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] In this energy-intensive process, a solution of alumina in a molten (940 and 970 °C (1,720 and 1,780 °F)) mixture of cryolite (Na3AlF6) with calcium fluoride is electrolyzed to produce metallic aluminium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The liquid aluminium sinks to the bottom of the solution and is tapped off, and usually cast into large blocks called aluminium billets for further processing.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Anodes of the electrolysis cell are made of carbon—the most resistant material against fluoride corrosion—and either bake at the process or are prebaked.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The former, also called Söderberg anodes, are less power-efficient and fumes released during baking are costly to collect, which is why they are being replaced by prebaked anodes even though they save the power, energy, and labor to prebake the cathodes.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Carbon for anodes should be preferably pure so that neither aluminium nor the electrolyte is contaminated with ash.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Despite carbon's resistivity against corrosion, it is still consumed at a rate of 0.4–0.5 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Cathodes are made of anthracite; high purity for them is not required because impurities leach only very slowly.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The cathode is consumed at a rate of 0.02–0.04 kg per each kilogram of produced aluminium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] A cell is usually terminated after 2–6 years following a failure of the cathode.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The Hall–Heroult process produces aluminium with a purity of above 99%.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Further purification can be done by the Hoopes process.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] This process involves the electrolysis of molten aluminium with a sodium, barium, and aluminium fluoride electrolyte.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The resulting aluminium has a purity of 99.99%.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Electric power represents about 20 to 40% of the cost of producing aluminium, depending on the location of the smelter.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium production consumes roughly 5% of electricity generated in the United States.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Because of this, alternatives to the Hall–Héroult process have been researched, but none has turned out to be economically feasible.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Recovery of the metal through recycling has become an important task of the aluminium industry.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Recycling was a low-profile activity until the late 1960s, when the growing use of aluminium beverage cans brought it to public awareness.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Recycling involves melting the scrap, a process that requires only 5% of the energy used to produce aluminium from ore, though a significant part (up to 15% of the input material) is lost as dross (ash-like oxide).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] An aluminium stack melter produces significantly less dross, with values reported below 1%.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] White dross from primary aluminium production and from secondary recycling operations still contains useful quantities of aluminium that can be extracted industrially.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The process produces aluminium billets, together with a highly complex waste material.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It reacts with water, releasing a mixture of gases including, among others, acetylene, hydrogen sulfide and significant amounts of ammonia.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Despite these difficulties, the waste is used as a filler in asphalt and concrete.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Its potential for hydrogen production has also been considered and researched.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The global production of aluminium in 2016 was 58.8 million metric tons.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It exceeded that of any other metal except iron (1,231 million metric tons).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is almost always alloyed, which markedly improves its mechanical properties, especially when tempered.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] For example, the common aluminium foils and beverage cans are alloys of 92% to 99% aluminium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The main alloying agents for both wrought and cast aluminium are copper, zinc, magnesium, manganese, and silicon (e.g., duralumin) with the levels of other metals in a few percent by weight.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium is the main substitute to copper and its applications to the traditional domains of copper have seen increased interest when copper prices are high such as in 2011–2014 and 2021.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] There is a competition in the use of aluminium and copper in the automotive industry, but in other uses such as in the construction industry and in underground and submarine cables aluminium has been largely unable to compete with copper.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The great majority (about 90%) of aluminium oxide is converted to metallic aluminium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Being a very hard material (Mohs hardness 9), alumina is widely used as an abrasive; being extraordinarily chemically inert, it is useful in highly reactive environments such as high pressure sodium lamps.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium oxide is commonly used as a catalyst for industrial processes; e.g. the Claus process to convert hydrogen sulfide to sulfur in refineries and to alkylate amines.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Many industrial catalysts are supported by alumina, meaning that the expensive catalyst material is dispersed over a surface of the inert alumina.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Another principal use is as a drying agent or absorbent.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Several sulfates of aluminium have industrial and commercial application.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium sulfate (in its hydrate form) is produced on the annual scale of several millions of metric tons.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] About two-thirds is consumed in water treatment.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] The next major application is in the manufacture of paper.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] It is also used as a mordant in dyeing, in pickling seeds, deodorizing of mineral oils, in leather tanning, and in production of other aluminium compounds.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Two kinds of alum, ammonium alum and potassium alum, were formerly used as mordants and in leather tanning, but their use has significantly declined following availability of high-purity aluminium sulfate.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Anhydrous aluminium chloride is used as a catalyst in chemical and petrochemical industries, the dyeing industry, and in synthesis of various inorganic and organic compounds.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Aluminium hydroxychlorides are used in purifying water, in the paper industry, and as antiperspirants.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p01] Sodium aluminate is used in treating water and as an accelerator of solidification of cement.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Despite its widespread occurrence in the Earth's crust, aluminium has no known function in biology.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] At pH 6–9 (relevant for most natural waters), aluminium precipitates out of water as the hydroxide and is hence not available; most elements behaving this way have no biological role or are toxic.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Aluminium sulfate has an LD50 of 6207 mg/kg (oral, mouse).
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Aluminium is classified as a non-carcinogen by the United States Department of Health and Human Services.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] A review published in 1988 said that there was little evidence that normal exposure to aluminium presents a risk to healthy adult, and a 2014 multi-element toxicology review was unable to find deleterious effects of aluminium consumed in amounts not greater than 40 mg/day per kg of body mass.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Most ingested aluminium is eliminated in feces, and much of what enters the bloodstream is excreted in urine; however, not all absorbed or parenterally administered aluminium is cleared through urinary excretion.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Aluminium, although rarely, can cause vitamin D-resistant osteomalacia, erythropoietin-resistant microcytic anemia, and central nervous system alterations.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] People with kidney insufficiency are especially at a risk.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Chronic ingestion of hydrated aluminium silicates (for excess gastric acidity control) may result in aluminium binding to intestinal contents and increased elimination of other metals, such as iron or zinc; sufficiently high doses (>50 g/day) can cause anemia.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] During the 1988 Camelford water pollution incident, people in Camelford had their drinking water contaminated with aluminium sulfate for several weeks.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] A final report into the incident in 2013 concluded it was unlikely that this had caused long-term health problems.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Aluminium has been suspected of being a possible cause of Alzheimer's disease, but research into this for over 40 years has found, as of 2018, no good evidence of causal effect.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Aluminium increases estrogen-related gene expression in human breast cancer cells cultured in the laboratory.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] In very high doses, aluminium is associated with altered function of the blood–brain barrier.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] A small percentage of people have contact allergies to aluminium and experience itchy red rashes, headache, muscle pain, joint pain, poor memory, insomnia, depression, asthma, irritable bowel syndrome, or other symptoms upon contact with products containing aluminium.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Exposure to powdered aluminium or aluminium welding fumes can cause pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Fine aluminium powder can ignite or explode, posing another workplace hazard.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Drinking water contains more aluminium than solid food; however, aluminium in food may be absorbed more than aluminium from water.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Dietary exposure in Europeans averages to 0.2–1.5 mg/kg/week but can be as high as 2.3 mg/kg/week.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Higher exposure levels of aluminium are mostly limited to plumbers, masons, electrical workers, machinists, and surgeons.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Consumption of antacids, antiperspirants, vaccines, and cosmetics provide possible routes of exposure.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Consumption of acidic foods or liquids with aluminium enhances aluminium absorption, and maltol has been shown to increase the accumulation of aluminium in nerve and bone tissues.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] In case of suspected sudden intake of a large amount of aluminium, the only treatment is deferoxamine mesylate which may be given to help eliminate aluminium from the body by chelation therapy.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] However, this should be applied with caution as this reduces not only aluminium body levels, but also those of other metals such as copper or iron.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] High levels of aluminium occur near mining sites; small amounts of aluminium are released to the environment at coal-fired power plants or incinerators.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Aluminium in the air is washed out by the rain or normally settles down but small particles of aluminium remain in the air for a long time.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Acidic precipitation is the main natural factor to mobilize aluminium from natural sources and the main reason for the environmental effects of aluminium; however, the main factor of presence of aluminium in salt and freshwater are the industrial processes that also release aluminium into air.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] In water, aluminium acts as a toxic agent on gill-breathing animals such as fish when the water is acidic, in which aluminium may precipitate on gills, which causes loss of plasma- and hemolymph ions leading to osmoregulatory failure.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Organic complexes of aluminium may be easily absorbed and interfere with metabolism in mammals and birds, even though this rarely happens in practice.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Aluminium is primary among the factors that reduce plant growth on acidic soils.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Although it is generally harmless to plant growth in pH-neutral soils, in acid soils the concentration of toxic Al3+ cations increases and disturbs root growth and function.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Wheat has developed a tolerance to aluminium, releasing organic compounds that bind to harmful aluminium cations.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Sorghum is believed to have the same tolerance mechanism.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Aluminium production possesses its own challenges to the environment on each step of the production process.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] The major challenge is the emission of greenhouse gases.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] These gases result from electrical consumption of the smelters and the byproducts of processing.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] The most potent of these gases are perfluorocarbons, namely CF4 and C2F6, from the smelting process.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] Biodegradation of metallic aluminium is extremely rare; most aluminium-corroding organisms do not directly attack or consume the aluminium, but instead produce corrosive wastes.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] The fungus *Geotrichum candidum* can consume the aluminium in compact discs.
[src:scissors/aluminium-p02] The bacterium *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* and the fungus *Cladosporium resinae* are commonly detected in aircraft fuel tanks that use kerosene-based fuels (not avgas), and laboratory cultures can degrade aluminium.
[src:scissors/scissors] While all scissors largely follow the same working principle, heavy-duty scissors intended for cutting tough materials tend to be called shears instead of scissors (e.g. pruning shears and grass shears), and some larger, two-handed implements are called *trimmers* instead (e.g. hedge trimmer).
[src:scissors/scissors] Choosing the optimal type of scissors/shears is crucial, as otherwise it can cause unwanted damage to the target material and/or the instrument itself.
[src:scissors/scissors] Surgical scissors, used to divide tissues and trim/reshape implants during surgical operations, have even a greater variety to deal with different anatomical and procedural circumstances.
[src:scissors/scissors] Most scissors have a ringed handle to allow readily opening for repeated cutting, and some even have spring between the shanks to assist opening (especially for shears with straight handle).
[src:scissors/scissors] While historically inexpensive, mass-produced scissors often have bare metal handles, modern scissors are often designed ergonomically with composite thermoplastic and rubber covering on handles, which are more comfortable for the hand.
[src:scissors/scissors] The noun *scissors* is treated as a plural noun and therefore takes a plural verb (e.g., *these scissors are*).
[src:scissors/scissors] Alternatively, the tool is referred to by the singular phrase *a pair of scissors*.
[src:scissors/scissors] The word *shears* is used to describe similar instruments that are larger in size and for heavier cutting.
[src:scissors/scissors] The Hangzhou Zhang Xiaoquan Company in Hangzhou, China, has been manufacturing scissors since 1663.
[src:scissors/scissors] Pivoted scissors were not manufactured in large numbers until 1761, when Robert Hinchliffe of Sheffield produced the first pair of modern-day scissors made of hardened and polished cast steel.
[src:scissors/scissors] His major challenge was to form the bows; first, he made them solid, then drilled a hole, and then filed away metal to make this large enough to admit the user's fingers.
[src:scissors/scissors] This process was laborious, and apparently Hinchliffe improved upon it in order to increase production.
[src:scissors/scissors] Hinchliffe lived in Cheney Square (now the site of Sheffield Town Hall), and set up a sign identifying himself as a "fine scissor manufacturer".
[src:scissors/scissors] He achieved strong sales in London and elsewhere.
[src:scissors/scissors] The vast majority of global scissor manufacturing takes place in China.
[src:scissors/scissors] As of 2019, China was responsible for 64.3% of worldwide scissors exports.
[src:scissors/scissors] When combined with Chinese Taipei exports, this rises to 68.3%.
[src:scissors/scissors] The Hangzhou Zhang Xiaoquan Company, founded in 1663, is one of the oldest continuously operating scissor manufacturers in the world.
[src:scissors/scissors] The company was nationalized in 1958 and now employs 1500 people who annually mass-produce an estimated seven million pairs of inexpensive scissors that retail for an average of US$4 each.
[src:scissors/scissors] In the late 14th century, the English word "scissors" came into usage.
[src:scissors/scissors] It was derived from the Old French word *cisoires*, which referred to shears.
[src:scissors/scissors] There are several historically important scissor-producing regions in France: Haute-Marne in Nogent-en Bassigny, Châtellereault, Thiers and Rouen.
[src:scissors/scissors] These towns, like many other scissor-producing communities, began with sabre, sword and bayonet production, which transitioned to scissors and other blades in the late 18th and early 19th centuries.
[src:scissors/scissors] Thiers, in the Puy-de-Dôme department of Auvergne, remains an important centre of scissor and cutlery production.
[src:scissors/scissors] It is home to both the Musée de la Coutellerie, which showcases the town's 800-year history of blade-making, as well as Coutellia, an industry tradeshow that advertises itself as one of the largest annual gatherings of artisanal blade-makers in the world.
[src:scissors/scissors] Germany was responsible for manufacturing just under 7% of global scissors exports in 2019.
[src:scissors/scissors] Often called "The City of Blades", Solingen, in North Rhine-Westphalia, has been a center for the manufacturing of scissors since medieval times.
[src:scissors/scissors] At the end of the 18th century it's estimated that there were over 300 scissorsmiths in Solingen.
[src:scissors/scissors] In 1995 the City of Solingen passed The Solingen Ordinance, an update to a 1930s law that decreed "Made in Solingen" stamps could only be applied to products almost entirely manufactured in the old industrial area of Solingen.
[src:scissors/scissors] In 2019 this applied to approximately 150 companies making high-quality blades of all kinds, including scissors.
[src:scissors/scissors] Friedrich Herder, founded in Solingen in 1727, is one of the oldest scissors manufacturers still operating in Germany.
[src:scissors/scissors] Premana, in Lecco Province, has its origins in ironworks and knife manufacturing beginning in the 16th century.
[src:scissors/scissors] In 1900 there were ten scissor manufacturing workshops, 20 in 1952 and 48 by 1960.
[src:scissors/scissors] Today, Consorzio Premax, an industrial partnership, organizes over 60 local companies involved in the manufacture of scissors for global markets.
[src:scissors/scissors] In 2019 Italy exported 3.5% of scissors manufactured globally.
[src:scissors/scissors] One of the oldest Premanese scissor manufacturing firms still in operation is Sanelli Ambrogio, which was founded in 1869.
[src:scissors/scissors] Scissormaking in Japan evolved from sword making in the 14th century.
[src:scissors/scissors] Seki, in Gifu Prefecture, was a renowned center of swordmaking beginning in the 1200s.
[src:scissors/scissors] After citizens were no longer permitted to carry swords, the city's blacksmiths turned to making scissors and knives.
[src:scissors/scissors] There are many specialized types of Japanese scissors, but sewing scissors were introduced by American Commodore Matthew Perry from the United States in 1854.
[src:scissors/scissors] The Sasuke workshop in Sakai City south of Osaka is run by Yasuhiro Hirakawa, a 5th generation scissorsmith.
[src:scissors/scissors] The company has been in operation since 1867.
[src:scissors/scissors] Yasuhiro Hirakawa is the last traditional scissormaker in Japan, making scissors in the traditional style where the blades are believed to be thinner, lighter and sharper than European scissors.
[src:scissors/scissors] In 2018 he was profiled in a documentary that featured a pair of his bonsai snips which retailed for US$35,000.
[src:scissors/scissors] In Solsona, Spain, scissor manufacturing began in the 16th century.
[src:scissors/scissors] At the industry's peak in the 18th century there were 24 workshops, organized as the Guild of Saint Eligius, the patron saint of knife makers.
[src:scissors/scissors] By the mid-1980s there were only two, and by 2021, Pallarès Solsona, founded in 1917 by Lluìs and Carles Pallarès Canal, and still family-operated, was the town's sole remaining artisanal scissor manufacturer.
[src:scissors/scissors] Sheffield was home to the first mass production of scissors beginning in 1761.
[src:scissors/scissors] By the 19th century there were an estimated 60 steel scissor companies in Sheffield.
[src:scissors/scissors] However, since the 1980s, industry globalization and a shift towards cheaper, mass-produced scissors created price deflation that many artisanal manufacturers could not compete with.
[src:scissors/scissors] The Sheffield scissor industry consisted of just two local companies in 2021.
[src:scissors/scissors] The two remaining Sheffield scissor manufacturers are William Whiteley, founded in 1760, and Ernest Wright, which was established in 1902.
[src:scissors/scissors] Both now focus on high-end/niche crafting of "products for life" rather than mass production.
[src:scissors/scissors] Between these two firms it is estimated that there are no more than ten "putter-togetherers" or "putters" who are the master-trained craftspeople responsible for high quality Sheffield scissor assembly.
[src:scissors/scissors] In 2020, Ernest Wright was recognized with the Award for Endangered Crafts by the British Heritage Crafts Association.
[src:scissors/scissors] There are two varieties of left-handed scissors.
[src:scissors/scissors] Many common left-handed scissors (often called "semi"-left-handed scissors) simply have reversed finger grips.
[src:scissors/scissors] The blades open and close as with right-handed scissors, so that users tend to pull the blades apart as they are cutting.
[src:scissors/scissors] This can be challenging for craftspeople as the blades still obscure the cut.
[src:scissors/scissors] "True" left-handed scissors have both reversed finger grips and reversed blade layout, like mirror images of right-handed scissors.
[src:scissors/scissors] A left-handed person accustomed to using semi-left handed scissors may find using true left-handed scissors difficult at first, as they may have learned to rely heavily on the strength of their thumb to pull the blades apart vs. pushing the blades together in order to cut.
[src:scissors/scissors] Some scissors are marketed as ambidextrous.
[src:scissors/scissors] These have symmetric handles so there is no distinction between the thumb and finger handles, and have very strong pivots so that the blades rotate without any lateral give.
[src:scissors/scissors] However, most "ambidextrous" scissors are in fact still right-handed in that the upper blade is on the right, and hence is on the outside when held in the right hand.
[src:scissors/scissors] Even if they cut successfully, the blade orientation will block the view of the cutting line for a left-handed person.
[src:scissors/scissors] True ambidextrous scissors are possible if the blades are double-edged and one handle is swung all the way around (to almost 360 degrees) so that what were the backs of the blades become the new cutting edges.
[src:scissors/scissors] U.S. patent 3,978,584 was awarded for true ambidextrous scissors.
